<div id='communityQuestionsWithAnswers'>
<div class='communityQuestionAndAnswer'>
<div class='communityQuestion'>
<div class='questionText'>
<a href="/questions/647154-do-the-different-stories-sometimes-make">Do the different stories sometimes make reading the book confusing or difficult? I enjoy different points of view, but sometimes the reading experience is ruined by me trying to keep all the views straight.</a>
</div>
<div class='communityQAFooter questionFooter'>
<ul class='questionFooterActions'>
<li class='footerItem like'>
<span class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_community_question_647154'><a id="like_count_community_question_647154" rel="nofollow" href="/rating/voters/647154?resource_type=CommunityQuestion"><span class="likesCount">5 likes</span></a>&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;<a rel="nofollow" class="jsLike like_it" href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F8389671-the-red-garden">like</a></span>

</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionTimestamp'>
<a href="/questions/647154-do-the-different-stories-sometimes-make">5 years ago</a>
</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionPermalink'>
<a href="/questions/647154-do-the-different-stories-sometimes-make">See all 6 answers</a>
</li>
</ul>
</div>

</div>
<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/42839452-kim-hoag"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1530194780i/42839452._UX100_CR0,0,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/42839452-kim-hoag">Kim Hoag</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">It is definitely not confusing, but it isn&apos;t completely satisfying, either. This is often my problem with short stories, I never really have time to g<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">It is definitely not confusing, but it isn't completely satisfying, either. This is often my problem with short stories, I never really have time to get invested in the characters. There are some I really liked but the threads are more important than the characters, so the story ends leaving me unsatisfied by its resolution.<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerFooter'>

