<div id="review_145364928" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/145364928" />
    <a title="Diane" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/938087-diane"><img alt="Diane" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1531246153p2/938087.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/145364928?book_show_action=true">Feb 02, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Diane" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Diane" href="/user/show/938087-diane">Diane</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer145364928" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15268964417036124227">From a summary: The Red Garden introduces us to the luminous and haunting world of Blackwell, Massachusetts. Hoffman offers a transforming glimpse of small-town America, presenting us with some three hundred years of passion, dark secrets, loyalty, and redemption in a web of tales. <br/><br/>I haven&apos;t read an Alice Hoffman book for a few years, but I was intrigued by this one right from the first page. There&apos;s something comforting about following families over a three hundred year period -- especially whe</span>
  <span id="freeText15268964417036124227" style="display:none">From a summary: The Red Garden introduces us to the luminous and haunting world of Blackwell, Massachusetts. Hoffman offers a transforming glimpse of small-town America, presenting us with some three hundred years of passion, dark secrets, loyalty, and redemption in a web of tales. <br /><br />I haven't read an Alice Hoffman book for a few years, but I was intrigued by this one right from the first page. There's something comforting about following families over a three hundred year period -- especially when they all return to their roots in Blackwell, MA. Hoffman included historical events such as the Civil War, the Influenza Epidemic of 1916 and World War II. It was her storytelling, though, that had me hooked throughout the book. I liked the characters, flaws and all. This book was a nice change of pace.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15268964417036124227" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


